Interesting numbers on the increasing proportion of serial entrepreneurs and other experienced founders going though @StartX.
Oh and if you're a Stanford alum with startup experience, same goes for you! Mentoring founders through StartX is rewarding and educational.
This StartX event is not actually a demo day as I mentioned earlier but Zendydesk's description just now was very compact and effective.
So if you're a recent/current Stanford student working on startups, check out @StartX. A unique benefit of the #gostanford experience.
When I was here there was nothing like StartX and so I'm glad to see this resource grow, and provide opportunities for alumni to engage too.
One of the characteristic features of @StartX's approach is there's always "Ask" time for founders to describe how the community can help.
Joseph will be sharing all that experience ‚Äì building, recruiting, operating, acquisition, beyond ‚Äì directly with future batches at StartX.
For example, Joseph Wang from WiFiSLAM (1st or 2nd batch, acquired by Apple) has returned to run programming at StartX.
that support means small teams come in and accelerate not just towards product fit, but also recruit Stanford-level talent and investors.
Basically, all participants are encouraged to continue paying it forward by returning as mentors or otherwise providing support ‚Äì
StartX funds startups without taking equity, which is basically unheard of, but that's just a small part of expanding the Stanford community

Are we pacing technologies with the processes necessary for their transformation into products? Are we ready?
What durable need is served here? When might the next capture, the next snapshot, be necessary?
So perhaps it is useful to consider not just the finished products, but the ongoing opportunities each product suggests for the future.
Even as needs remain constant, and technology develops without limit (without the burdens of the productization process, for one thing!).
But they are moments in time, these products. And so they will become outmoded, less useful, quaint.
And they will often be wildly successful in their time: the correct product formulation will transfer the power of technology to serve need.
In between those needs and tools, there will be people who periodically bridge the gap with the right interface ‚Äì the right product.
That is, there will always be some constant human need (ex. communication) and new technologies (ex. undersea cable, radio, photography).
Actually there are three elements: the parallel constants of technology and human needs, and the more periodic productization in between.
Software and services too: operating system, worldwide directory, search, assistant
Recent needs that captured/froze technology in the form of products: the mainframe, the desktop, the laptop, the smartphone, the tablet
Each of those becomes a product that solves some problem or does some job.
But this holds true for older technologies too: petrochemicals, paper, mechanical gears, flaked flint
Go to any hardware component convention to see the rapidly curing edge where technology starts to become productized: chips, LEDs, sensors
By comparison to usable product, technology can be considered formless: infinite potential but without an interface to the world.
I think of productization as the moment in time we choose to give useful form to available technology.
That is, where do products come from? Necessity and market demand are big drivers, as are insightful people who make key conceptual leaps.
But at a higher level, and with a more long-term view, what is productization?
As an industry and even as users, we have some understanding of the skills and processes that allow us to arrive at useful, usable products.
Thankfully we now talk much more fluently about design and product management than we did twenty or even ten years ago.

@msquinn "ambient" is pretty good and probably taken by the likes of Alexa! I am looking for something more single-user & "non-living room"
One day we'll look at smartphones like we look at old modems, with their quirky handshakes and noisy dial-up sequences. Hurdles to the data.
"Pulling out a phone isn't that inconvenient!" But add in finding the app, launching it, navigating, typing a query, picking a result...
But my answer for "what's next" is to shorten the interval between impulse and result, so that close to 100% of interaction is productive.
We will still need the gadgets ‚Äì visually scanning and reading are very efficient for true consumption. Screens won't go away completely.
But the "special room" has become the gadget: these totems we carry and activate in order to gain entry to that parallel layer ("cloud").
We early adopters are now creating and consuming information and entertainment from nearly anywhere, at any time.
The smartphone created "addressable user minutes" because we could "compute" anywhere, not just in special rooms at home, work, school.
The smartphone miniaturized the networked computer so that we could take our information consumption and sharing out into the world.
But the big idea is, we won't have to activate our computers (phones, watches) to access services anymore. The services will just be there.
And maybe it'll be AR after all, with elegant glasses and clever menus. Though eye commands/cursors have deep issues of their own.
It could be a nightmare of muttering at first. Early adopters sounding crazy as they walk down the street mumbling commands.
We won't be consciously glancing at phones/watches, waiting for battery-constrained screens/chips to wake up. We'll just say what we want.
Perpetual is around the corner: Alexa/Siri 2.0, all-day earpieces, faster ubiquitous wireless. Today's chatbots will pioneer Perpetual apps.
Defining trait of Perpetual is that is always there, ready. Not peripheral like phone or goggles, which require fetching/donning to begin.
VR/AR will be compatible with perpetual, but not required. And not truly perpetual until VR goggles evolve into glasses or similar.
Perpetual implies true voice recognition (not the current misnomer for command recognition) per user. Nuanced. Detects stress/urgency.
Perpetual means a constant, companion presence that is ready to serve and understands context. Probably a low voice/earpiece interface.

So my pitch tip would be to know your audience. A certain kind of investor wants to see the rough details as well as the polished slides.
I imagine anyone who has been early at a good startup would recognize the "side project". Powerful signal for investors who have operated.
To me it's proof I'm talking to people that are a little further along in the game, beyond the idea stage. Validation of the Team slide too.
Often it's mentioned off-hand or even bashfully as a little script or spreadsheet they use to capture process, but I always ask for details.
A valuable startup pattern I keep seeing: team mentions supporting project to automate growth or other user behavior they've discovered.
